     <p><strong><p><strong>Richard Bourke, <em>Hegel’s World Revolutions</em>, Princeton University Press, 2023, 344pp., $29.95 (pbk), ISBN 9780691253121.</strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Bernardo Ferro, University of Coimbra</strong></p>
     <p>Paul Ricoeur famously singled out Marx, Nietzsche, and Freud as three “masters of suspicion”, bent on looking beneath the surface of modern Western reason (1970: 32). Despite their many differences, all three denounced Enlightenment rationalism as an artificial construction, rooted in a covert set of economic or psychological motivations, and their criticisms have cast a long historical shadow. In <em>Hegel’s World Revolutions</em>, Richard Bourke aims to challenge this critical trend. He focuses, more precisely, on how the cultural pessimism that emerged during the late nineteenth century has shaped contemporary thought and on the favour it currently enjoys in academic and intellectual circles. In his eyes, “what started out as an eccentric tradition of historical reflection”, launched by Nietzsche and generalized by Heidegger, Adorno and Foucault,...
